      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The Maillard reaction is a chemical reaction between amino acids and reducing sugars that gives browned food its distinctive flavor. This reaction typically occurs at temperatures above 140°C (284°F), much higher than the caramelization process, which happens at a lower temperature, around 160°C (320°F). The Maillard reaction is responsible for the golden-brown crust on bread, while caramelization contributes to the flavor and color of the crust. So, it's not just a matter of browning, but also the creation of complex flavors that are essential to the taste of bread.",
